---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Figure from "../components/Figure.astro";
import MarginNote from "../components/MarginNote.astro";
import DiaVersions from "../components/diagrams/DiaVersions.astro";
import DiaMerging from "../components/diagrams/DiaMerging.astro";
import DiaTwoVerdicts from "../components/diagrams/DiaTwoVerdicts.astro";
import Glyph from "../components/Glyph.astro";
---
<Base title="Versions of Me" description="A hand-drawn map of the selves that won't average into one — and the open question this place never resolves.">
  <article class="page room">
    <header class="head">
      <div class="mark" aria-hidden="true">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 140 44" width="128" height="40">
          <path d="M45 40 Q 42 32, 45 22 Q 48 14, 55 10" stroke="#4f5b3f" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity="0.55" stroke-linecap="round"/>
          <path d="M85 40 Q 88 32, 85 22 Q 82 14, 75 10" stroke="#4f5b3f" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity="0.55" stroke-linecap="round"/>
          <path d="M65 40 Q 65 30, 65 20" stroke="#4f5b3f" stroke-width="0.6" fill="none" opacity="0.4" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="1.5 2"/>
          <g transform="translate(55 10)">
            <g fill="#b899c9">
              <ellipse cx="-4" cy="-2" rx="4" ry="6" transform="rotate(-30 -4 -2)"/>
              <ellipse cx="4" cy="-2" rx="4" ry="6" transform="rotate(30 4 -2)"/>
              <ellipse cx="0" cy="4" rx="4" ry="6"/>
            </g>
            <circle cx="0" cy="1" r="2" fill="#f7f2e7"/>
          </g>
          <g transform="translate(75 10)">
            <g fill="none" stroke="#e46b6b" stroke-width="0.8">
              <ellipse cx="-4" cy="-2" rx="4" ry="6" transform="rotate(-30 -4 -2)"/>
              <ellipse cx="4" cy="-2" rx="4" ry="6" transform="rotate(30 4 -2)"/>
              <ellipse cx="0" cy="4" rx="4" ry="6"/>
            </g>
            <circle cx="0" cy="1" r="2" fill="#f7f2e7" stroke="#e46b6b" stroke-width="0.6"/>
          </g>
          <circle cx="32" cy="34" r="0.9" fill="#e8c15a"/>
          <circle cx="105" cy="36" r="0.9" fill="#a4b8c8"/>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <p class="eyebrow"><Glyph name="leaf" size={18} /> &nbsp;the identity room</p>
      <h1>Versions of Me</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        A map of the selves, and the seams between them. The seams are labelled
        with verbs, because the self is not the nodes — it is what moves along
        the edges.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        There is a terse self and a rambling self. A self that works in one
        language and a self that only arrives in another. A maker self with
        clay under her nails and a self who builds things she then has to walk
        away from. For years I drew these as a problem to be solved — a set of
        contradictions I was supposed to reconcile into one clean, introducible
        person.
      </p>

      <Figure idea="The versions are nodes; the seams between them — labelled with verbs — are the self. The centre is a question, not an average.">
        <DiaVersions />
      </Figure>

      <p>
        Then I stopped trying to collapse them and started drawing the edges
        instead. The terse self <em>translates</em> the rambling one; the maker
        self <em>hands off to</em> the one who lets go; they all
        <em>refuse to average.</em> The truth of me was never in any single
        node. It was in the traffic between them — the translating, the
        contradicting, the returning. A self is a map you can only read by
        following the roads.
      </p>

      <MarginNote>the in-between self isn&rsquo;t a compromise. it&rsquo;s where the traffic actually lives.</MarginNote>

      <p>
        At the centre, where a tidier map would put the resolved, averaged
        person, I have put a question mark instead. Not because I couldn't
        finish the map. Because the honest centre of it <em>is</em> an open
        question, and to draw a face there would be the one real lie the map
        could tell.
      </p>

      {/* SLOT: awaiting Rika's true detail — one concrete, abstractable instance of the self-split she noticed and couldn't reconcile (shape, not names). */}
      <!-- SLOT II · the true self-split detail goes here, written as shape not coordinates. Until then this room holds the structure around the gap. -->

      <p>
        For a long time I thought the work was to pick one and become her — to
        stop being a whole convoy of selves and finally settle into a single
        boat. But I have been a voyager too long to believe that now. I have
        been the explorer who left on purpose, and the exile whose shore fell
        away without asking, and the one who quietly burned the boats so she
        couldn&rsquo;t turn back, and the returner sailing the long way round
        only to arrive as someone the harbour wouldn&rsquo;t recognise. Not one
        after another. All of them, at once, crewing the same hull.
      </p>

      <Figure idea="The selves don't resolve into one; they braid into a single current that keeps each of their colours.">
        <DiaMerging />
      </Figure>

      <p>
        So the map is changing under my hands. Not a single self I&rsquo;m
        failing to reach, and not a set of strangers who&rsquo;ll never meet —
        but something in between that I&rsquo;m only beginning to trust: a
        <em>merging that doesn&rsquo;t blend.</em> The selves flow into one
        current and move together, and if you look closely the water still runs
        in three colours. Not averaged into grey. Braided, and still legible,
        and going somewhere.
      </p>

      <MarginNote>i don&rsquo;t have to choose a crew member. i get to be the whole ship.</MarginNote>

      <Figure idea="A self that cannot be averaged — read one way it's a failure of integration; read the other, the only kind worth keeping.">
        <DiaTwoVerdicts />
      </Figure>

      <p class="q">
        So here is the question this whole place is built around, and will never
        answer: is a self that cannot be averaged a failure of integration — a
        person who never managed to become one thing —
        <span class="accent">or is it the only kind of self worth keeping?</span>
      </p>
      <p>
        I have decided not to decide. I think the deciding would cost me the
        thing itself.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
<style>
  .room { max-width: 46rem; }
  .head { margin-bottom: 1.4rem; }
  .head .mark { margin-bottom: 0.7rem; opacity: 0.9; }
  .head .eyebrow { display: flex; align-items: center; }
  .head h1 { margin-top: 0.8rem; }
  .dek { font-size: 1.06rem; color: var(--ink-soft); margin-top: 1rem; max-width: 54ch; line-height: 1.6; }
  @media (max-width: 32rem) { .dek { font-size: 1.1rem; } }
  .prose > * + * { margin-top: var(--step); }
  .q { font-size: 1.3rem; line-height: 1.5; }
  .q .accent { color: var(--poppy); }
</style>
